    "cwd": "/tmp/bla",
    "prompt": "## Part B: Build the Process Monitor (~90 minutes)\n\nBuild a lightweight process monitoring system with two components: a **server** that collects metrics and a **client** that gathers them from the local system.\n\n### Server (`pmon-server`)\n\n- Accepts one or more PIDs as CLI arguments\n- Listens for TCP connections from monitoring clients\n- Assigns each connecting client a PID to monitor\n- Every 30 seconds, prints a summary: which clients are connected, what they're monitoring, latest CPU/memory metrics\n- Handles client disconnects (stale entries should not persist)\n\n### Client (`pmon-client`)\n\n- Connects to the server via TCP\n- Receives a PID assignment from the server\n- Uses the [`sysinfo`](https://docs.rs/sysinfo) crate to read CPU and memory usage of the assigned process every 10 seconds\n- Sends metrics to the server\n- Handles gracefully: monitored process exits, connection loss\n\n### Design Decisions\n\nWe intentionally leave these choices to you. There's no single correct answer — we want to see how you think about tradeoffs. **Favor simplicity and clarity** — a straightforward text-based protocol over plain TCP is perfectly fine. We're evaluating your design reasoning, not protocol sophistication.\n\n- **Wire protocol**: How do client and server exchange messages? How do you handle message boundaries over TCP? (A simple approach is fine — explain why you chose it.)\n- **Client identity**: How does the server identify and track individual clients?\n- **PID assignment**: What happens when more clients connect than there are PIDs to monitor? What happens when a client disconnects — does its PID become available again?\n- **Error recovery**: What does the client do when the monitored process disappears? When the connection drops?\n- **Shutdown**: How do both components shut down cleanly on Ctrl+C (SIGINT)?\n\n### Requirements\n\n1. Cargo workspace with `pmon-server` and `pmon-client` as separate binary crates (shared library crate optional)\n2. No panics on expected errors (disconnects, invalid data, process not found)\n3. Graceful shutdown on SIGINT for both binaries\n4. Tests for protocol parsing logic and at least one scenario covering the core metrics flow\n5. `README.md` with: build/run instructions, wire protocol design with rationale, error handling approach, what you'd add given more time",
