    "prompt": "#1 is funny. the disagreement means that i always expected to be taking design decisions and that i was planning something bigger in my mind already.\n#2 that's correct. and that's the part i'm really not sure about. a component always depends on its interfaces and most of the domains in our product leak outside of their component also into their interface. this happens naturally and is a completely valid thing for a monolith. however that's where this breaks, as we will have to deal with legacy interfaces and expectations of that interfaces that the old implementation provided, but the new one will not anymore, at least not without additional work (or taking side-effects into account). not sure how we will deal with this. our modernizations of sensors and probe were a success, however it took more legacy behavior into account that we would have liked (we planned to do things differently, but we couldn't because we would have had to change the consumer side as well and that was always the classic core - the thing we now want to rework)\n#3 exactly\n#4 right. this is a scary one. right now i have an interim manager (heidrun) that will take care of my team until someone new joins as a replacement for robin. when this takes up speed, i'm sure raj will take care of this by his own. however raj is also on a 6 month contract to kickoff org restructuring together with markus (who also leaves - lol). i'm really not sure how this will go...\n#5 also correct. but i'm sure when we frame the apollo project a bit differently from \"let's just do something to replace the delphi core\" to \"let's build a new product\" we will get more of peoples attention.\n\ni'm sure the org will not be ready on wednesday. but when i have raj on my side this will be planned into the new org since day 1 (maybe not as \"apollo\" anymore).\nbtw: brett (also with apollo since day 2) will leave mid of april. that leaves me as the last member of the initial apollo team LOL",
